In Java, an ExecutorService is a framework that manages a pool of threads and a queue of tasks. Instead of you manually calling new Thread().start(), the executor decides when and how to run your tasks.
With the arrival of Java 21, these executors are now divided into two main categories: Thread-Pooling (Old/Standard) and Thread-Per-Task (New/Virtual).
1. The Virtual Thread Executor (The New Standard)
This is the one we used for your Salesforce project. It does not "pool" threads because virtual threads are disposable.
 * Executors.newVirtualThreadPerTaskExecutor()
   * How it works: For every task you submit, it creates a brand-new virtual thread.
   * Best for: I/O-bound tasks (API calls, DB queries).
   * Resource usage: Extremely low memory; can handle millions of concurrent tasks.
2. Fixed Thread Pool (The "Workhorse")
 * Executors.newFixedThreadPool(nThreads)
   * How it works: It creates a set number of Platform (OS) threads. If all threads are busy, new tasks wait in a queue.
   * Best for: CPU-bound tasks (Complex math, image processing, sorting large lists).
   * Resource usage: High. Each thread takes ~1MB of memory.
3. Cached Thread Pool (The "Elastic" Pool)
 * Executors.newCachedThreadPool()
   * How it works: It creates new threads as needed but reuses old ones that have finished. If a thread is idle for 60 seconds, it is terminated.
   * Best for: Many short-lived tasks where you don't know the volume in advance.
   * Danger: If you submit 100,000 tasks at once, it will try to create 100,000 OS threads and likely crash your server.
4. Single Thread Executor (The "Ordered" Worker)
 * Executors.newSingleThreadExecutor()
   * How it works: Uses exactly one thread. Tasks are guaranteed to execute one after another (FIFO).
   * Best for: Sequential processing where you must ensure Task A finishes before Task B starts (e.g., writing to a specific log file).
5. Scheduled Executor (The "Timer")
 * Executors.newScheduledThreadPool(nThreads)
   * How it works: Allows you to delay a task or run it periodically (e.g., every 5 minutes).
   * Best for: Heartbeats, cleaning up temp files, or polling a status every few seconds.
Comparison Table: Which one should you pick?
| Scenario | Recommended Executor | Thread Type |
|---|---|---|
| Salesforce/API Calls | newVirtualThreadPerTaskExecutor | Virtual |
| Database Heavy I/O | newVirtualThreadPerTaskExecutor | Virtual |
| Video Encoding / Math | newFixedThreadPool(CPU_CORES) | Platform |
| Background Cron Job | newScheduledThreadPool | Platform |
| Sequential File Write | newSingleThreadExecutor | Platform |
